Smart Real Estate Insights Engine (SRIE)¶

Project Overview¶

I am building a ML-driven pipeline that can accurately predict rental prices while also providing business-friendly insights into real estate trends.
Instead of just another price prediction model, I’m building something that truly adds value—a Smart Real Estate Insights Engine (SRIE) that:

  • Predicts rent prices with high accuracy
  • Explains the pricing factors behind each prediction
  • Detects anomalies and pricing outliers
  • Is cost-efficient, scalable, and easy to integrate

Why This Approach?¶

  • SQL-Based Data Pipeline → Real-time data ingestion and seamless integration
  • Cost-Efficient Models →
  • Explainability & Trust → SHAP-based insights to justify pricing recommendations
  • Deployment-Ready → Can be integrated into Client's homebuying platform

Next Steps¶

  • Load dependencies and set up the notebook
  • Ensure modularity and efficiency before moving forward

Handling Missing Data¶

In [9]:

Approach for Handling Missing Values:¶

  • Categorical Features:
    • Fill missing laundry_options and parking_options with "unknown" to preserve information without introducing bias.
  • Numerical Features:
    • Fill missing lat and long with the median of their respective region to maintain geographical accuracy.
    • Compute price_per_sqft based on price and sqfeet where possible; otherwise, use median price per sqft from similar properties
In [10]:
# Filling categorical missing values
train_df["laundry_options"].fillna("unknown", inplace=True)
train_df["parking_options"].fillna("unknown", inplace=True)

# Fill missing lat/long using regional median values
train_df["lat"] = train_df["lat"].fillna(train_df.groupby("region")["lat"].transform("median"))
train_df["long"] = train_df["long"].fillna(train_df.groupby("region")["long"].transform("median"))

# Compute price_per_sqft where missing
train_df["price_per_sqft"] = train_df["price"] / train_df["sqfeet"]
median_price_sqft = train_df.groupby("region")["price_per_sqft"].median()

# Apply median price per sqft for missing values
train_df.loc[train_df["price_per_sqft"].isnull(), "price_per_sqft"] = train_df["region"].map(median_price_sqft)

# Verifying if missing values are handled
missing_values_after = train_df.isnull().sum()
print("Missing Values After Cleaning:\n", missing_values_after[missing_values_after > 0])

Missing Values After Cleaning:
 description    2
dtype: int64

Since the description column is unlikely to be used directly in our ML pipeline, we can safely replace missing values with "No description provided" to maintain dataset consistency.

Feature Engineering & Transformation¶

To improve the model’s predictive power, I’ll create new features and transform existing ones to ensure they are model-ready. This includes:

  • Deriving meaningful property-specific metrics like price_per_sqft.
  • Encoding categorical variables to numerical format.
  • Scaling numerical features to standardize values across different scales.
  • Ensuring that feature selection aligns with business needs.
In [12]:
# Feature: Price per Bedroom
train_df["price_per_bed"] = train_df["price"] / train_df["beds"]
train_df["price_per_bed"].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan, inplace=True)
train_df["price_per_bed"].fillna(train_df["price"].median(), inplace=True)

# Feature: Price per Bathroom
train_df["price_per_bath"] = train_df["price"] / train_df["baths"]
train_df["price_per_bath"].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan, inplace=True)
train_df["price_per_bath"].fillna(train_df["price"].median(), inplace=True)

# Feature: Pets Allowed Indicator
train_df["pets_allowed"] = (train_df["cats_allowed"] | train_df["dogs_allowed"]).astype(int)

# Feature: Total Amenities Count
train_df["total_amenities"] = (
    train_df["pets_allowed"] + train_df["smoking_allowed"] +
    train_df["wheelchair_access"] + train_df["electric_vehicle_charge"] +
    train_df["comes_furnished"]
)

# Feature: Number of Listings per Region
train_df["region_listings"] = train_df.groupby("region")["id"].transform("count")

Analyze Categorical Columns¶

Before choosing an encoding strategy, let's examine:

  • Number of unique values → Helps determine whether to use One-Hot, Binary, or Ordinal encoding.
  • Distribution of values → Ensures balanced representation and avoids sparsity.
  • Potential impact on the model → Avoiding unnecessary high-dimensionality.

Selecting Encoding Methods¶

Given the unique value counts, here’s the optimal approach for each column:

  1. One-Hot Encode → laundry_options, parking_options, and type.
  2. Binary Encode → state.
  3. Feature Engineer region → Instead of encoding all 404 values, we use "region_listings" (number of listings per region) to capture its impact.
  4. Drop or Process description → If needed, we can use NLP-based embeddings.

Scaling Numerical Features¶

To ensure that all numerical features are on a comparable scale, I will apply Min-Max Scaling, which normalizes values between 0 and 1.

Why Min-Max Scaling?¶

  • Preserves relationships between variables.
  • Prevents large values (like price and sqfeet) from dominating.
  • Essential for models like XGBoost, Linear Regression, and Neural Networks.

Features to Scale¶

  • sqfeet, beds, baths
  • price_per_sqft, price_per_bed, price_per_bath
  • region_listings (number of listings in each region)

Model Training (Baseline & Optimized Models)¶

To ensure we build an effective rental price prediction model, I will train two models:

  • Baseline Model: Linear Regression → Establishes a simple benchmark.
  • Optimized Model: XGBoost → Provides a balance of accuracy and efficiency.

Why XGBoost?¶

  • Handles missing values internally.
  • Works well with structured tabular data.
  • Optimized for both speed and performance.
In [27]:

Evaluating Linear Regression Performance¶

The Linear Regression model performed decently with an R² score of 0.8580, meaning it explains 85.8% of the variance in rent prices. However, the high error values (MAE: 847, RMSE: 22,351) suggest potential issues:

Observations from Linear Regression Results¶

R² = 0.8580 → Model is capturing a good portion of the variance in rent prices.
MAE = 847 → On average, predictions are off by $847, which might not be ideal.
RMSE = 22,351 → Large errors indicate outliers or non-linearity in the dataset.

XG Boost¶

Since Linear Regression may not be complex enough for real estate pricing, we move to a more robust model: XGBoost.

Why Train XGBoost?¶

  • Can capture non-linear relationships that Linear Regression cannot.
  • Handles feature interactions automatically.
  • Less sensitive to outliers compared to regression models.

Identifying the Issue¶

Since XGBoost should normally outperform Linear Regression on complex datasets, we need to diagnose why it's failing:

Re-check Feature Importance¶

  • Are some features dominating too much?
  • Are we using irrelevant or redundant features?
  • Does feature importance suggest we should drop some features?

Selecting Meaningful Feature Interactions¶

Based on the mutual information (MI) scores and correlation analysis, we can make data-driven decisions about which interactions to create.

Key Observations¶

  • price_per_bath (MI: 5.99) and price_per_bed (MI: 5.93) are the most important predictors of price.
  • price_per_sqft (MI: 4.01) is also highly relevant.
  • The three features (price_per_sqft, price_per_bed, and price_per_bath) are highly correlated (>0.88), indicating they capture similar information.
  • sqfeet, region_listings, and baths have moderate predictive power.
  • beds and total_amenities have low MI scores, meaning they have a weaker relationship with price.

Decision: Which Interactions to Create?¶

  1. Avoid Redundant Features

    • Since price_per_sqft, price_per_bed, and price_per_bath are strongly correlated, we do not need to create multiple interaction terms with them.
    • Instead, we select only one primary interaction that represents size-based pricing.

  2. Create price_sqft_region (price_per_sqft × region_listings)

    • Rationale:
      • price_per_sqft captures local rental pricing trends.
      • region_listings represents supply density in the region.
      • Multiplying them provides insight into whether high-demand regions impact pricing per sqft.

  3. Create beds_baths (beds × baths)

    • Rationale:
      • Number of bedrooms and bathrooms together defines home capacity.
      • A 1-bed/1-bath vs. 3-bed/2-bath home has different rental pricing power.
      • Multiplying them can enhance model differentiation.

# Define the objective function
def objective(trial):
    params = {
        "n_estimators": trial.suggest_int("n_estimators", 100, 1000, step=100),
        "learning_rate": trial.suggest_loguniform("learning_rate", 0.005, 0.1),
        "max_depth": trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 3, 10),
        "subsample": trial.suggest_float("subsample", 0.6, 1.0),
        "colsample_bytree": trial.suggest_float("colsample_bytree", 0.6, 1.0),
        "reg_alpha": trial.suggest_loguniform("reg_alpha", 1e-4, 10.0),
        "reg_lambda": trial.suggest_loguniform("reg_lambda", 1e-4, 10.0),
    }

    model = xgb.XGBRegressor(**params, random_state=42, eval_metric="rmse")

    # Train the model and manually implement early stopping
    model.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_test, y_test)], verbose=False)

    # Make predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Return RMSE for evaluation
    return mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred) ** 0.5 # RMSE

# Run optimization
study = optuna.create_study(direction="minimize")
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=20)

# Get best parameters
best_params = study.best_params
print("Best XGBoost Hyperparameters:", best_params)

# Train final model with best parameters

# Define models
models = {
    "Linear Regression": LinearRegression(),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),
    "LightGBM": lgb.LGBMRegressor(n_estimators=300, learning_rate=0.05),
    "CatBoost": cb.CatBoostRegressor(iterations=300, learning_rate=0.05, verbose=0),
    "XGBoost (Tuned)": xgb_best
}


# Train and evaluate each model
results = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred) ** 0.5
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

    results[name] = {"MAE": mae, "RMSE": rmse, "R²": r2}


df_results = pd.DataFrame(results).T
display(df_results)

1. Model Selection Analysis¶

Current Performance Comparison¶

Model MAE ↓ RMSE ↓ R² ↑
Linear Regression 760.12 22,349.35 0.86
Random Forest 76.30 14,993.16 0.94
LightGBM 1146.68 59,824.77 -0.017
CatBoost 956.22 70,070.43 -0.39
XGBoost (Tuned) 696.06 55,003.29 0.14
  • Random Forest is currently the best-performing model in terms of R² (0.94) and RMSE (14,993). It significantly outperforms other models.
  • XGBoost (even after fine-tuning) is still underperforming, with an R² of only 0.14. This suggests that the model isn't learning well from the given feature set.
  • LightGBM and CatBoost have negative R², meaning they are worse than just predicting the mean rent price.
  • Linear Regression is surprisingly doing well, achieving an R² of 0.86, which suggests the problem might be more linear than expected.

Why is XGBoost Failing?¶

  • Feature Interactions Not Helping: The created interaction features (price_sqft_region, beds_baths) have strong theoretical reasoning but did not contribute significantly in SHAP or feature importance.
  • Feature Importance Mismatch: Our best manually created features are not appearing in the top feature importance rankings, suggesting that the model is not utilizing them effectively.
  • Overfitting or Insufficient Learning? XGBoost might be underfitting rather than overfitting. Fine-tuning helped slightly, but the final RMSE (55,000+) suggests it struggles to learn the pattern correctly.

Hybrid Model¶

  • Idea: Use a Linear Regression + Random Forest Ensemble.
  • Why?: Linear Regression does well with broad trends, while RF captures non-linear patterns.
